WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.360
Welcome back!

2
00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:09.360
In this video, we'll review how trading impacts the lender's profit and the fees charged to borrowers.

3
00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:13.200
As seen earlier, the financial system is a big loop that

4
00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.920
transports money from those who have too much to those who have too little.

5
00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:25.120
We learned that when lenders sell their mortgage loans to investors, they can make money on the trade, called a premium.

6
00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:28.840
Lenders also make money by charging fees to borrowers.

7
00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:34.400
So lenders have two ways of making money: through fees and trade premiums.

8
00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:41.000
This sounds too good to be true for lenders; they can make so much money from this process, right?

9
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:42.240
Well yes!

10
00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:43.440
And no.

11
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:46.240
Lenders can make a lot of money.

12
00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:50.240
They don't have total control over how much they make.

13
00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:53.840
This is because lending is a highly competitive market.

14
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:59.320
A competitive market has many buyers and sellers for identical or similar products.

15
00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:05.920
Per the Consumer Finance Protection Bureau, there were 4,338 mortgage

16
00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:13.080
lenders and 23 point 3 million loan applications in the United States for 2021.

17
00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:19.440
Because of all the participants in the market, no one buyer or seller could set a price.

18
00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:20.440
Why?

19
00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:26.320
In a highly competitive market, picking the right price is like a game of tug-of-war: if a

20
00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:33.160
lender charges more than their competitors, they may lose the sale to another lender charging less.

21
00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:36.040
And if the lender charges too little, they might not make

22
00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:39.800
enough money to pay their employees and they will go out of business.

23
00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:43.400
So lenders are constantly analyzing their profit margins to

24
00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:47.680
ensure they are in line with the market and not over or undercharging.

25
00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:53.120
Profit is simply the money made after all expenses have been paid.

26
00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:57.160
Mathematically, it is revenue minus expenses.

27
00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:00.760
Revenue is the total money made from doing business.

28
00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:06.280
In lending, this would be any fees as well as trade premiums earned.

29
00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:10.400
Expenses are the business costs, for example, paying the

30
00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:15.640
mortgage banker, office expenses, or discounts given to the borrower.

31
00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:18.400
Let's put this all together with an example.

32
00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:24.120
If revenue is 50,000 and expenses are 30,000, what is profit?

33
00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:29.920
We would simply subtract expenses from revenue and have 20,000 left over.

34
00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:37.360
Loan profit margin is specific to lending and refers to the percent of the profit earned for every dollar lent.

35
00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:41.320
Mathematically, it is just profit divided by the loan amount.

36
00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:50.720
For example, a loan with 14,000 in profit and a loan amount of 100,000 would have a loan profit margin of 14%.

37
00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:54.480
Every business has a target profit they aim to achieve.

38
00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:59.720
If you were to start a painting company, how would you know how much to charge for a job?

39
00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:05.200
Usually, you'd start with the cost of materials and labor and then apply your target margin.

40
00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:07.280
Lenders also operate this way.

41
00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:13.960
They aim to make a certain profit margin based on the fees they charge and the premium they make from trading.

42
00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:17.120
Having higher margins is not always a good thing.

43
00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.760
Because of the competitive nature of the lending, when profit margins are higher

44
00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:26.560
than their target, it may be an indication that the business is charging too much.

45
00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:32.400
In a competitive market, they could be losing customers due to their higher prices, so it

46
00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:39.280
may be best to lower prices to remain competitive within the market and capture more customers.

47
00:03:39.280 --> 00:03:46.600
And when profit is lower than the target, the lender needs to raise prices; otherwise, they risk going out of business.

48
00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:50.080
Lenders generate income from trading their mortgages on the capital

49
00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:57.120
markets, so they are sensitive to trading activities and the financial markets.

50
00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:04.880
This is why when you hear about central banks raising or lowering interest rates, pay attention: it impacts you!

51
00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:11.640
The lender must change their rates and fees when markets change to maintain their target profit.

52
00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:16.720
Alright, let's put this knowledge to use and analyze our trading data.

